Subsample all repertoires to the same depth

200 iterations

Compute robustness of sharing

You retain exact CDR3 sequences while correcting for depth.

🧠 Additional Important Considerations
Define clonotype identity carefully:

AA CDR3 only?

AA + V gene?

Nucleotide?

Publicness depends strongly on this.

Consider generation probability (Pgen)

Using models like OLGA:

High-Pgen sequences are expected to be public

You can compare observed sharing vs expected sharing

📊 Practical Workflow

Filter non-productive TRB

Define clonotype key (e.g., CDR3aa + TRBV + TRBJ)

Remove singletons (optional)

Rarefy to min depth

Repeat 200×

Compute:

Number of individuals sharing

Stability of sharing across iterations

####
Below is a fully implementable Python solution (PyMC v5) for:

Step 4 — Fit hierarchical detection model

Step 5 — Compute posterior probability that a clonotype is shared in ≥ N individuals

Step 6 — Perform robustness / sensitivity checks

This version is:

Statistically principled

Computationally tractable for ~10⁴–10⁵ clonotypes (batched)

Explicitly depth-corrected

Publication-ready

🔬 MODEL STRUCTURE (Computationally Practical Version)

W
I have TRB repertoires from 3 groups of individuals. I would like to build a ML model which would find  how these groups differ in their TRB repertoires. Sharing sequences are not very probable, but should be an option; I suspect it is more about specific aminoacid properties of these sequences. What modelling would be appropriate and state of the art, for publication?

Got it — you’re essentially asking about ML models for TCR repertoire classification (multi-group) based on TRB sequences, where exact sequence sharing is rare, and you suspect differences are biophysical/structural properties of the CDR3 sequences. I can break this down carefully.

1️⃣ Key characteristics of your problem
Feature	Notes
Data	TRB repertoires from 3 groups (healthy, disease, etc.)
Sequence sharing	Rare → k-mer or motif approaches may be sparse
Signal type	Likely physicochemical / biochemical patterns in CDR3
Task	Multi-class classification (3 groups)
Goal	Identify repertoire-level patterns, publishable insights

So your problem is repertoire-level supervised learning with sparse, structured sequence data.

2️⃣ Representation options for TCR sequences

The representation of TRB sequences is crucial:

a) Amino acid / physicochemical embeddings

Encode CDR3 sequences into vectors:

One-hot encoding of AAs

AA indices: hydrophobicity, charge, polarity, size

Biochemical property vectors: e.g., from Kidera or Atchley factors

Pros: captures biochemical similarity beyond exact sequence

Cons: sequences of variable length → need padding, masking, or summarization

b) k-mer / motif features

Break CDR3 into overlapping k-mers (e.g., k=3–5)

Count/frequency table per repertoire

Pros: handles sequence variability

Cons: sparse, high dimensionality

c) Learned embeddings from pre-trained models

TCR-specific language models:

TCR-BERT, DeepTCR embeddings

ELMo, ProtBert, UniRep (protein language models)

Encode sequences into fixed-size embeddings, then aggregate per repertoire

Pros: state-of-the-art; captures sequence context, physicochemical properties

d) Repertoire-level aggregation

Because your labels are per individual / repertoire, not per sequence:

Sum / mean of sequence embeddings

Attention-based weighted pooling (DeepTCR / TCR-BERT)

Spectral clustering or bag-of-sequences approaches

3️⃣ Modelling approaches
a) Classical ML

Use aggregated features per repertoire (k-mer counts, AA property summaries)

Models:

Random Forest

Gradient Boosted Trees (XGBoost, LightGBM)

SVM

Pros: interpretable, fast

Cons: may lose sequence context

b) Deep learning

Sequence-based neural networks:

CNNs over AA sequences

1D convolutions over one-hot or embedded sequences

Capture local motifs

Pool across sequences → repertoire-level

Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs / LSTM / GRU)

Process sequences of variable length

Pool hidden states per repertoire

Attention / Transformers

DeepTCR and TCR-BERT use transformers

Attention allows learning which sequences or motifs contribute most

c) Repertoire-level methods

Some modern methods treat the repertoire as a bag of sequences:

DeepTCR (Sidhom et al., 2021, Nat Methods
)

Uses sequence embeddings + attention

Can perform classification, motif discovery, repertoire-level prediction

Handles rare sequence sharing well

tessa / immuneML (https://github.com/airlab-unibas/immuneML
)

ML framework for TCR/BCR repertoires

Supports k-mer, motif, and deep learning features

Multi-class classification

GLIPH2 (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31987047/
)

Clustering CDR3 sequences by motifs

Then ML on motif counts per repertoire

d) Graph-based / network approaches

Build sequence similarity networks

Node = unique CDR3, edge = biochemical similarity

Compute graph metrics per repertoire → classical ML

4️⃣ Practical workflow for publication-quality analysis

Preprocessing

Filter low-quality sequences

Trim/pad CDR3 sequences

Annotate V/J genes

Feature representation

Option 1: k-mer counts / AA property summaries → classical ML

Option 2: Pre-trained embeddings → deep learning / attention

Option 3: Hybrid: k-mer + physicochemical features

Aggregate per individual

Mean/sum of embeddings

Attention-weighted aggregation (DeepTCR style)

Model training

Random forest / XGBoost → baseline

Deep learning with attention → state-of-the-art

Evaluation

Multi-class accuracy / ROC-AUC per class

Cross-validation across individuals

Test generalization on held-out repertoires

Interpretation

Feature importance (for k-mers / AA properties)

Attention weights → motifs driving classification

Compare group differences in repertoire diversity / motifs

5️⃣ References / State-of-the-art
Method	Notes
DeepTCR	Attention-based classification and motif discovery from TCR repertoires
immuneML	Framework for classical ML & deep learning on immune repertoires
TCR-BERT / ProtBERT	Embeddings from protein language models
GLIPH2	Motif-based clustering; downstream ML on motif counts
Random Forest / XGBoost	Strong baseline on k-mer / physicochemical features
6️⃣ Key recommendations

Do not rely on exact sequence sharing — your representation must generalize to unseen sequences.

AA properties and embeddings are more powerful than raw k-mers.

Attention or pooling is essential for per-repertoire labels.

Baseline classical ML helps with interpretability and review expectations.

If you want, I can draft a concrete pipeline for your 3-group TRB repertoires:

Preprocessing

Feature engineering (AA properties + k-mer + embeddings)

ML model (classical + DeepTCR style)

Repertoire-level aggregation

Cross-validation & feature interpretation

DeepTCRhttps://github.com/sidhomj/DeepTCR.git

